  },
  {
    "client_msg_id": "d616cfb2-6b7b-4c36-9025-56f283f95d20",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "Mathematicians by and large have not been much interested in computer programming as a field. For one, mathematics is at its core the study of pattern, and computer programming is very messy and patterns are hard to come by. Also, it doesn't lend itself to any proofs, because even a simple game like Snake can't be proven to be perfect, partly because there are subjective/aesthetic aspects to defining \"correct\" in a game. I myself am interested in measuring robustness in computer programs, especially as it relates to comparing two languages. Which language has the lowest propensity for error? Can one through the design of a language, make it much more difficult o create an error? I call it the Calculus of Error, and after using Modula-2 for example when everyone else was using C, i found that M2 programs were smaller, faster, and much more reliable, so there are intrinsic characteristics in a language which are measurable. In our industry we haven't been willing to tell the truth about the weaknesses in various languages, preferring to categorize things as mere preference. Without measurement you have fad and fashion.",
    "user": "UEQ6M68H0",
    "ts": "1552892344.052000",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
