  {
    "client_msg_id": "ea99ba5c-5d9f-4c74-842d-b509f16447c6",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "Hi Robin, welcome to the group :wink:\nI'd be interested in your previous work, is it available online somewhere?\nMy personal story with math is that I can only really understand most things once I've build a spacial mental model for them. I think about differentiation / integration in terms of diagrams, about gradient descend as arrows pointing downwards hills and so on. I believe that these representations are incredibly useful because they leverage our well-developed spacial imagination. In my opinion, there's a huge potential for good visualizations or even interactively explorable explanations to help people think about mathematical concepts. Like <@UCGAK10LS> mentioned already, 3blue1brown's youtube channel is a very good example of this. Another good place to find cool explorable explanations is in this subreddit: <https://www.reddit.com/r/explorables/>\nFinally, I've created an interactive visualization of the Hough Transform myself some time ago: <https://fkohlgrueber.github.io/blog/hough-transform/>\nWhile the visualization by itself doesn't teach the concept very well, I believe that tools like these could be really helpful to teachers trying to show more than a couple of static examples on slides.",
    "user": "UAL7940NM",
    "ts": "1552899196.052300",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
